----------------------------------- FatBoot -----------------------------------

FatBoot is a collection of small boot sector programs that
fit in a single sector (512 bytes) and written in NASM assembly language
for Intel 8086-compatible CPUs, utilizing IBM PC-compatible BIOS interrupts.

FatBoot allows you to easily boot your low-level programs just by copying them
to the filesystem root.

Each program performs the following:
  1. Relocates itself from the default boot address (0x7C00) to the lowest
     possible (0x500, right above the IVT and BDA).
  2. Loads the specified file from the filesystem root to the specified
     segment:offset.
  3. Jumps to the specified segment:offset.

Each program supports non-standard disk and filesystem configurations, such as
sector size, cluster size, number of FAT tables, etc. Moreover, all programs
support both CHS and LBA addressing methods, making them work on old
machines and applicable to both hard and floppy drives, all in 512 bytes!

---------------------------- How to set up FatBoot ----------------------------

To apply a boot sector program to your media run:

    ./apply.sh <target> <filesystem> <offset> <load_filename>
                   <load_to_seg:off> <jump_to_seg:off>

For example, to apply FatBoot to a FAT16 partition, first sector of which
is located in the 64th sector of /dev/fda, so that it loads KERNEL.BIN
to 0x0000:0x1000 and jumps to 0x0100:0x0100, run:

    ./apply.sh /dev/fda FAT16 63 KERNEL.BIN 0x0000:0x1000 0x0100:0x0100

